Airports in the United States

Lets load a list of airport data from https://github.com/jpatokal/openflights

airports <- read.csv("airports.dat", header = FALSE)
colnames(airports) <- c("ID", "name", "city", "country", "IATA_FAA", "ICAO", "lat", "lon", "altitude", "timezone", "DST", "Region")

This data set contains airports from all over the world. Lets get only the airports from the United States.

library(dplyr)
## Warning: package 'dplyr' was built under R version 3.2.5
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
usa_airports <- airports %>% filter(country == "United States")

library(DT)
datatable(usa_airports[,c("name", "city", "country", "IATA_FAA", "lat", "lon", "altitude")])

Lets generate a static map containing the location of all of the airports in the USA

library(ggmap)
map <- get_map(location = "Seattle, WA", zoom = 3)
ggmap(map) + geom_point(aes(x = lon, y = lat), data = usa_airports, alpha = 0.25)

Lets generate a zoomable, pannable map using the leaflet package. Here you can see airports that belong to the USA that arent geographically within the borders of the United States.

library(leaflet)
m <- leaflet(data = usa_airports) %>%
  addTiles() %>%  # Add default OpenStreetMap map tiles
  addCircles(~lon, ~lat, popup = ~name)
m  # Print the map
